com.oceanoptics.omnidriver.features.gpio

Interface GPIO


  • public interface GPIO
    This interface applies to classes that support General Purpose I/O (GPIO). GPIO functionality is typically provided through an FPGA.

    Intended devices are HR4000, QE65000, USB2000+, HR2000+, USB4000

    • Method Detail

      • getValueBits

        java.util.BitSet getValueBits()
                       throws java.io.IOException
        Reads the states of all value bits and return them as a BitSet. The value bits correspond to pins that the user may connect to.
        Returns:
        A BitSet with the value bit states. The size of the BitSet reflects the total number of bits that the device supports.
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException - is thrown if the device's GPIO bits cannot be read.

      • getValueBit

        int getValueBit(int bitNumber)
         throws java.io.IOException
        Reads the state of the specified GPIO bit. The GPIO bits correspond to pins that the user may connect to.
        Parameters:
        bitNumber - A number 0-N specifying which GPIO bit to examine.
        Returns:
        An integer value of 0 or 1, depending on the state of the specified bit.
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException - is thrown if the device's GPIO bits cannot be read.

      • setValueAllBits

        void setValueAllBits(java.util.BitSet bitSet)
              throws java.io.IOException
        Asserts a new state for the GPIO value bits. The value bits correspond to the pins available to the user.
        Parameters:
        bitSet - A BitSet containing the new state to push to the GPIO. Note that bits in excess of the number reported by getTotalBits() may be ignored.
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException - is thrown if the device's GPIO bits cannot be written.

      • setValueBit

                 boolean value)
          throws java.io.IOException
        Asserts a new state for the GPIO value bits. The value bits correspond to the pins available to the user.
        Parameters:

      • getDirectionBits

        java.util.BitSet getDirectionBits()
                           throws java.io.IOException
        Reads the states of all direction bits and return them as a BitSet. The direction bits specify whether a particular pin is set as input (false) or output (true).
        Returns:
        A BitSet with the direction bit states. The size of the BitSet reflects the total number of bits that the device supports. A pin is input if its corresponding bit is false, and output otherwise.
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException - is thrown if the device's GPIO bits cannot be read.

        Parameters:
        bitSet - A BitSet containing the new state to push to the GPIO. Note that bits in excess of the number reported by getTotalBits() may be ignored.
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException - is thrown if the device's GPIO bits cannot be written.
